{"award_age":51.0,"bio_image":"full\/4d1e87c5d721060a10a44ecfd830f65d22005131.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"Norway","date_of_birth":"1963-01-04T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"female","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/e\/e9\/May-Britt_Moser_2014.jpg\/220px-May-Britt_Moser_2014.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/May-Britt_Moser","mini_bio":"<p><b>May-Britt Moser<\/b> (born 4 January 1963) is a Norwegian <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Psychologist\" title=\"Psychologist\">psychologist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neuroscientist\" title=\"Neuroscientist\">neuroscientist<\/a>, and founding director of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kavli_Institute_for_Systems_Neuroscience_and_Centre_for_the_Biology_of_Memory\" title=\"Kavli Institute for Systems Neuroscience and Centre for the Biology of Memory\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Kavli Institute<\/a>. She and her husband, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edvard_Moser\" title=\"Edvard Moser\">Edvard<\/a>, pioneered research on the brain's mechanism for representing space. They shared the 2014 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel prize in Physiology or Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_O%27Keefe_(neuroscientist)\" title=\"John O'Keefe (neuroscientist)\">John O'Keefe<\/a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/May-Britt_Moser#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> awarded for work concerning the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Grid_cells\" title=\"Grid cells\" class=\"mw-redirect\">grid cells<\/a> that make up the positioning system in the brain.<\/p><p>The Mosers were appointed associate professors in psychology and neuroscience at NTNU in 1996, less than one year after their Ph.D defenses. They established The Centre for the Biology of Memory (CBM) in 2002 and the Kavli Institute for Systems Neuroscience and Centre for the Biology of Memory at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norwegian_University_of_Science_and_Technology\" title=\"Norwegian University of Science and Technology\">Norwegian University of Science and Technology<\/a> (NTNU) in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Trondheim,_Norway\" title=\"Trondheim, Norway\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Trondheim, Norway<\/a>, the fifteenth<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">[<i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wikipedia:Please_clarify\" title=\"Wikipedia:Please clarify\"><span title=\"The text near this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. (March 2015)\">clarification needed<\/span><\/a><\/i>]<\/sup> in the world and the fourth in neuroscience, in 2007.<\/p>","name":"May-Britt Moser","place_of_birth":"Fosnav\u00e5g ,  Norway","place_of_death":null,"text":"May-Britt Moser , Physiology or Medicine, 2014","year":2014.0}